on consciousness and the deliberative powers of citizens. The second is that an alternative path toward a critical social ontology can provide a framework for a new theory of ethics and politics. This critical social ontology looks at human sociality not as mere intersubjectivity or communication, but rather as constituted by the shapes that our social-relational structures take as well as the kinds of purposes and ends toward which our social lives are organized. Only by calling these into question, Thompson boldly argues, can we once again attempt to revitalize social critique and democratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical theory. 0aOntology. 0aPolitical sociology. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aSociology : Social Problems. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848037440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480374/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles